```js
if (dosesTaken === dosesRequired) {
  console.log('All doses taken — great job!');
} else if (dosesTaken < dosesRequired) {
  const remaining = dosesRequired - dosesTaken;
  console.log(`${remaining} dose(s) remaining today`);
} else {
  console.log('Something seems off — check with your doctor');
}
```

The third condition (else) catches the 'impossible' case where doses taken > required — always worth handling edge cases.

```js
const calculateGrade = (score) => {
  if (score >= 90) return 'A';
  if (score >= 80) return 'B';
  if (score >= 70) return 'C';
  if (score >= 60) return 'D';
  return 'F';
};

console.log(calculateGrade(95)); // A
console.log(calculateGrade(73)); // C
console.log(calculateGrade(52)); // F
```

Early returns make the logic clean — each condition is independent. When a return fires, the function stops. No need for else after each if.
